4 WHEREAS, Powell was also named the National Wild Turkey Federation's
5 Arkansas Officer of the Year; and
6
7 WHEREAS, in addition to these impressive awards, Powell received a
8 Lifesaving Award along with fellow Game Warden Aaron Dillard for their
9 bravery and heroic efforts to save a girl being swept downstream by the
10 Mississippi River current and barge wakes by working quickly to get her into
11 their boat and back to shore safely; and
12
13 WHEREAS, Powell was also featured in a "Scales of Justice" article in
14 the June 2024 issue of Arkansas Wildlife for his work in using shot shell
15 forensics and DNA analysis to prove that two (2) Mississippi turkey hunters
16 were using Arkansas hunting licenses to illegally hunt turkeys; and
17
18 WHEREAS, Colonel Brad Young, the Arkansas State Game and Fish
19 Commission Chief of Enforcement said this about Powell: "We're very, very
20 proud of him. He had some very hard to make cases. It took a lot of hours
21 to apprehend some of those violators"; and
22
23 WHEREAS, Powell's hard work in focusing on major violators resulted in
24 twelve (12) charges of night hunting, thirteen (13) charges of road hunting,
25 seventeen (17) charges for hunting during a closed season, four (4) charges
26 for boating while under the influence, five (5) cases of hunting turkey over
27 bait, eight (8) cases for hunting without permission, four (4) cases for
28 hunting waterfowl over bait, and three (3) cases for falsifying information;
29 and
30
31 WHEREAS, in December 2024 in Augusta, Georgia, Powell was once again
32 recognized for his hard work and dedication when he was named the
33 Southeastern Association of Fish and Wildlife Agencies 2024 Robert M. Brantly
34 Law Enforcement Officer of the Year; and
35
